# ====Verbal nouns / gerunds ====
# Verbal nouns are forms of verbs that allow one to use a verb phrase as a noun phrase.  An example in English might be "running" in the sentence "I like running", or "eating beshbarmaq with my hands" in "I believe in eating beshbarmaq with my hands".  The former sentence in Kazakh would be:
# ::{{gl|Мен|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|nom}}|I}}
# {{gl|жүгіруді|жүгір{{tag|v}}{{tag|iv}}{{tag|ger}}{{tag|acc}}|running}}
# {{gl|жақсы|жақсы{{tag|adv}}|well}}
# {{gl|көремін|көр{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|aor}}{{tag|p1}}{{tag|sg}}|I see}}
# ::{{glend|"I like running."}}
# 
# You can also embed subjects, kind of like the English "I saw him/his running home."
# 
# ::{{gl|Мен|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|nom}}|I}}
# {{gl|оның|ол{{tag|prn}}{{tag|gen}}|his}}
# {{gl|үйге|үй{{tag|n}}{{tag|dat}}|to home}}
# {{gl|қарай|қарай{{tag|pst}}|towards}}
# {{gl|жүгіретінін|жүгір{{tag|v}}{{tag|iv}}{{tag|ger_impf}}{{tag|px3sp}}{{tag|acc}}|his running}}
# {{gl|көрдім|көр{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|ifi}}{{tag|p1}}{{tag|sg}}|I saw}}
# ::{{glend|"I saw him running home."}}
# 
# This same sentence could also be translated as follows, depending on whether you're focusing on the fact that he was running (previous) or that you saw him run home (following):
# ::{{gl|Мен|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|nom}}|I}}
# {{gl|оның|ол{{tag|prn}}{{tag|gen}}|his}}
# {{gl|үйге|үй{{tag|n}}{{tag|dat}}|to home}}
# {{gl|қарай|қарай{{tag|pst}}|towards}}
# {{gl|жүгіргенін|жүгір{{tag|v}}{{tag|iv}}{{tag|ger_prf}}{{tag|px3sp}}{{tag|acc}}|his running}}
# {{gl|көрдім|көр{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|ifi}}{{tag|p1}}{{tag|sg}}|I saw}}
# ::{{glend|"I saw him run home."}}
# 
# As implied by this example, while the tense of gerunds is limited in English, gerunds in most Turkic languages can have a wide range of tense/mood/aspect/evidentiality (TMAE) combinations.  Many of these are translated to languages like English as subordinate clauses, e.g. "I believe that he eats beshbarmaq with his hands.":
# ::{{gl|Беспармақ|беспармақ{{tag|n}}{{tag|acc}}|beshbarmaq}}
# {{gl|қолымен|қол{{tag|n}}{{tag|px3sp}}{{tag|inst}}|with his hands}}
# {{gl|жейтініне|же{{tag|v}}{{tag|ger_impf}}{{tag|px3sg}}{{tag|dat}}|to his eating}}
# {{gl|сенемін|сен{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|aor}}{{tag|p1}}{{tag|sg}}|I believe}}
# ::{{glend|I believe that he eats beshbarmaq with his hands."}}
# 
# Notice that in these examples, the verb phrase is being used as a subject, object, adjunct, etc.  That is, in Turkic languages, gerunds can take any grammatical role (and morphology) that a noun phrase can take.  In Kazakh, for example, the verbal nouns can take any combination of possession and/or case suffixes.  They may sometimes even take plural suffixes, though often forms that appear to be a gerund followed by a plural suffix are actually plural substantivised [[#Verbal adjectives|verbal adjectives]] ({{tag|gpr}}{{tag|subst}}{{tag|pl}}).
# 
# For Turkic languages in apertium, the most fundamental gerund of a language (often used as an infinitive form) takes the {{tag|ger}} tag and other gerunds take tags based on {{tag|ger}} and something about their TMAE specification, such as {{tag|ger_impf}} (for "imperfective gerund") or {{tag|ger_fut}} (for "future gerund").
# 
# ====Verbal adjectives ====
# Verbal adjectives are forms of verbs that allow one to use a verb phrase as an adjectival phrase.  An example in English might be "running" in the sentence "The running man startled me" (as opposed to "the sitting man"), or "running home" in "The man running home startled me" (as opposed to "the man eating beshbarmaq").  These sentences in Kazakh would be:
# 
# :{{gl|Жүгіретін|жүгір{{tag|v}}{{tag|vi}}{{tag|gpr_impf}}|running}}
# {{gl|адам|адам{{tag|n}}{{tag|nom}}|man}}
# {{gl|мені|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|acc}}|me}}
# {{gl|шошытты.|шошы{{tag|v}}{{tag|iv}}{{tag|caus}}{{tag|ifi}}{{tag|p3}}{{tag|sg}}|he startled.}}
# :{{glend|"That running man startled me."}}
# 
# :{{gl|Үйге|үй{{tag|n}}{{tag|dat}}|to home}}
# {{gl|жүгіретін|жүгір{{tag|v}}{{tag|vi}}{{tag|gpr_impf}}|running}}
# {{gl|адам|адам{{tag|n}}{{tag|nom}}|man}}
# {{gl|мені|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|acc}}|me}}
# {{gl|шошытты.|шошы{{tag|v}}{{tag|iv}}{{tag|caus}}{{tag|ifi}}{{tag|p3}}{{tag|sg}}|he startled.}}
# :{{glend|"The man running home startled me."}}
# 
# Notice that while in English verbal adjective phrases that are longer than just a verb must be placed after the noun they modify, in Kazakh verbal adjective phrases of any length are only ever placed before the noun.
# 
# Phrases formed using verbal adjectives in Turkic languages are often translated using relative clauses in languages like English (e.g., "The man who was running [home] startled me.").  Note that in Turkic languages, usually any part of the verb phrase can be relativised (i.e., "extracted" from the embedded verb phrase and made into a nominal argument which the verbal adjective phrase then "modifies").  For example, "The man who I gave a fork to yesterday was eating beshbarmaq" and "The man that gave me a fork yesterday was eating beshbarmaq" can both be translated into Kazakh using verbal adjectives.
# 
# :{{gl|Кеше|кеше{{tag|adv}}|yesterday}}
# {{gl|мен|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|nom}}|I}}
# {{gl|шанышқы|шанышқы{{tag|n}}{{tag|acc}}|fork}}
# {{gl|берген|бер{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|gpr_past}}|having given}}
# {{gl|адам|адам{{tag|n}}{{tag|nom}}|man}}
# {{gl|беспармақ|беспармақ{{tag|n}}{{tag|nom}}|beshbarmaq}}
# {{gl|жеп|же{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|prc}}|eating}}
# {{gl|жатқан.|жат{{tag|vaux}}{{tag|past}}{{tag|p3}}{{tag|sg}}|was}}
# :{{glend|"The man who I gave the fork to yesterday was eating beshbarmaq."}}
# 
# :{{gl|Кеше|кеше{{tag|adv}}|yesterday}}
# {{gl|маған|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|dat}}|to me}}
# {{gl|шанышқы|шанышқы{{tag|n}}{{tag|acc}}|fork}}
# {{gl|берген|бер{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|gpr_past}}|having given}}
# {{gl|адам|адам{{tag|n}}{{tag|nom}}|man}}
# {{gl|беспармақ|беспармақ{{tag|n}}{{tag|nom}}|beshbarmaq}}
# {{gl|жеп|же{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|prc}}|eating}}
# {{gl|жатқан.|жат{{tag|vaux}}{{tag|past}}{{tag|p3}}{{tag|sg}}|was}}
# :{{glend|"The man who gave me the fork yesterday was eating beshbarmaq."}}
# 
# In English, there is a difference between relative clauses that limit/restrict (what's the right term?) the noun and those that don't.  E.g., "The man that I saw yesterday startled me" (specifically that mean startled me) versus "The man, who I saw yesterday, startled me" (a man startled me; it happens that I saw him yesterday).  In Turkic languages the default meaning of a verbal adjective is usually the restricted meaning, e.g. in Kazakh:
# 
# :{{gl|Мен|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|nom}}|I}}
# {{gl|кеше|кеше{{tag|adv}}|yesterday}}
# {{gl|көрген|көр{{tag|v}}{{tag|vt}}{{tag|gpr_past}}|seen}}
# {{gl|адам|адам{{tag|n}}{{tag|nom}}|man}}
# {{gl|мені|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|acc}}|me}}
# {{gl|шошытты.|шошы{{tag|v}}{{tag|iv}}{{tag|caus}}{{tag|ifi}}{{tag|p3}}{{tag|sg}}|he startled.}}
# :{{glend|"The man I saw yesterday startled me."}}
# 
# To get the non-restricted meaning in a Turkic language, two finite verb forms would normally be used (e.g., "The man scared me; I saw him yesterday").
# 
# Verbal adjectives can also be substantivised to mean "the ones who ...".  For example, in Kazakh, in a translation of the sentence "the ones/people I saw yesterday were eating beshbarmaq", "the ones/people I saw yesterday" would be formed like the first part of "the man I saw yesterday", but without the word "man", and a plural marker instead:
# 
# :{{gl|Мен|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|nom}}|I}}
# {{gl|кеше|кеше{{tag|adv}}|yesterday}}
# {{gl|көргендер|көр{{tag|v}}{{tag|vt}}{{tag|gpr_past}}{{tag|subst}}{{tag|pl}}|ones seen}}
# {{gl|беспармақ|беспармақ{{tag|n}}{{tag|nom}}|beshbarmaq}}
# {{gl|жеп|же{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|prc}}|eating}}
# {{gl|жатқан.|жат{{tag|vaux}}{{tag|past}}{{tag|p3}}{{tag|pl}}|were}}
# :{{glend|"The ones/people I saw were eating beshbarmaq."}}
# 
# For Turkic languages in apertium, the tags for verbal adjectives are based on {{tag|gpr}}, with a brief TMAE specification following, such as {{tag|gpr_past}} (for "past-tense verbal adjective") or {{tag|gpr_impf}} (for "imperfect verbal adjective").  The abbreviation "gpr" comes from the Russian phrase "<b>г</b>лагольное <b>пр</b>илагательное" [<b>g</b>laˈgolʲnəjɪ <b>pr</b>ʲilaˈgatʲɪlʲnəjɪ], which means "verbal adjective".
# 
# ====Participles ====
# Participles are verb forms that allow a verb phrase to be combined with other verbs for the purpose of adding information about tense/mood/aspect/voice/evidentiality (TMAVE) to the utterance.  That is, it's usually used in the creation of "compound verb tenses", so the following word is almost always a [[#Verbal auxiliaries|verbal auxiliary]], and the participial verb phrase and auxiliary together form <b>only one predicate</b>.
# 
# Examples of relevant compound verb phrases in Kazakh include the following:
# {|class="wikitable"
# |-
# ! gloss !! gloss !! participle
# |-
# | тамақ жеп біттің || ‘you finished eating’ || ^жеп/же{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|prc_prf}}$
# |-
# | тамақ жей бердің || ‘you kept eating’ || ^жей/же{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|prc_impf}}$
# |-
# | тамақ жейтін шығармын || ‘I seem to be eating’ || ^жейтін/же{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|prc_irre}}$
# |-
# | тамақ жесең болады || ‘you may/can eat’ || ^жесең/же{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|prc_cnd}}{{tag|p2}}{{tag|sg}}$
# |-
# | тамақ жегің келеді || ‘you want to eat’ || ^жегің/же{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|prc_vol}}{{tag|p2}}{{tag|sg}}$
# |-
# | тамақ жегелі жатырсың || ‘you're about to eat’ || ^жегелі/же{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|prc_purp}}$
# |-
# |colspan="3"| etc.
# |}
# 
# Some Turkic participles must agree with their subjects (in person, number, and formality), as with Kazakh's {{tag|prc_cnd}} and {{tag|prc_vol}} above, and most (but not all!) of them also have negative forms.  Examples of negative forms of participles include Kazakh ^ жемей/же{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|neg}}{{tag|prc_prf}}$ and ^жемейтін/же{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|neg}}{{tag|prc_irre}}$.
# 
# For Turkic languages in apertium, the tags for participles are based on {{tag|prc}}, with a brief TMAE specification following, such as {{tag|prc_impf}} (for "imperfective participle") or {{tag|prc_irre}} (for "irrealis participle").  The abbreviation "prc" comes from the English term "participle" or the Russian equivalent "причастие" [prʲiˈtɕastʲijɪ].
# 
# Most participles, along with most verbal adverbs, are often referred to as "converbs" in the Turkology literature.
# 
# ====Verbal adverbs ====
# Verbal adverbs are forms of verbs that allow one to use a verb phrase as an adjunct to another verb phrase.  Each verb phrase (the main one, and the one subordinated by the verbal adverb) is an independent predicate, resulting in ''two separate predicates''.  Use of these forms often relates two events to one another in some way temporally.  An example of a verbal adverb in English is "running" in "Running home, I saw that man".  In Kazakh, a similar sentence could be rendered as:
# 
# :{{gl|Үйге|үй{{tag|n}}{{tag|dat}}|to home}}
# {{gl|жүгіріп|жүгір{{tag|v}}{{tag|iv}}{{tag|gna}}|having run}}
# {{gl|мен|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|nom}}|I}}
# {{gl|сол|сол{{tag|det}}|that}}
# {{gl|адамды|адам{{tag|n}}{{tag|acc}}|man}}
# {{gl|көрдім.|көр{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|ifi}}{{tag|p1}}{{tag|sg}}|I saw.}}
# :{{glend|"Having run home, I saw that man."}}
# 
# Another example can be found in the following Kazakh sentence:
# 
# :{{gl|Мен|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|nom}}|I}}
# {{gl|сол|сол{{tag|det}}|that}}
# {{gl|адамды|адам{{tag|n}}{{tag|acc}}|man}}
# {{gl|көрсем|көр{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|gna_cond}}{{tag|p1}}{{tag|sg}}|if I see}}
# {{gl|үйге|үй{{tag|n}}{{tag|dat}}|to home}}
# {{gl|жүгіремін|жүгір{{tag|v}}{{tag|iv}}{{tag|aor}}{{tag|p1}}{{tag|sg}}|I will run}}
# :{{glend|"If I see that man, I will run home."}}
# 
# Some Turkic verbal adverbs must agree with their subjects (in person, number, and formality), as with Kazakh's {{tag|gna_cnd}} above, and almost all of them also have negative forms.  Examples of negative forms of participles include Kazakh ^жемей/же{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|neg}}{{tag|gna}}$ and ^жемесең/же{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|neg}}{{tag|gna_cond}}{{tag|p2}}{{tag|sg}}$.  Verbal adverbs can have the same or a different subject as the main verb phrase.
# 
# Some forms that are not morphologically verbal adverbs are used in very much the same way as verbal adverbs in Turkic languages.  For example, in Kazakh, a form like ^жүгіргенде/жүгір{{tag|v}}{{tag|iv}}{{tag|ger_past}}{{tag|loc}}$ allows a verb phrase with the verb "жүгір" to be used as an adjunct to another verb phrase, for example in the following sentences in Kazakh:
# 
# :{{gl|Үйге|үй{{tag|n}}{{tag|dat}}|to home}}
# {{gl|жүгіргенде|жүгір{{tag|v}}{{tag|iv}}{{tag|ger_past}}{{tag|loc}}|running}}
# {{gl|мен|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|nom}}|I}}
# {{gl|сол|сол{{tag|det}}|that}}
# {{gl|адамды|адам{{tag|n}}{{tag|acc}}|man}}
# {{gl|көрдім.|көр{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|ifi}}{{tag|p1}}{{tag|sg}}|I saw.}}
# :{{glend|"Running home, I saw that man."}}
# 
# :{{gl|Үйге|үй{{tag|n}}{{tag|dat}}|to home}}
# {{gl|жүгіргеннен|жүгір{{tag|v}}{{tag|iv}}{{tag|ger_past}}{{tag|abl}}|running}}
# {{gl|бері|бері{{tag|post}}|since}}
# {{gl|мен|мен{{tag|prn}}{{tag|nom}}|I}}
# {{gl|сол|сол{{tag|det}}|that}}
# {{gl|адамды|адам{{tag|n}}{{tag|acc}}|man}}
# {{gl|көрген жоқпын.|көр{{tag|v}}{{tag|tv}}{{tag|neg}}{{tag|past}}{{tag|p1}}{{tag|sg}}|I have not seen.}}
# :{{glend|"Since running home, I have not seen that man."}}
# 
# This is much like English expressions like "While running home, I saw that man" or "Since running home I have not seen that man", where a subordinating "conjunction" or a preposition is used.
# 
# For Turkic languages in apertium, the most fundamental verbal adverb of a language takes the {{tag|gna}} tag and other verbal adverbs take tags based on {{tag|gna}}, with a brief TMAE specification following, such as {{tag|gna_cnd}} (for "conditional verbal adverb").  The abbreviation "gna" comes from the Russian word "<b>г</b>лагольное <b>на</b>речие" [<b>g</b>laˈgolʲnəjɪ <b>na</b>ˈrʲetɕijɪ], meaning literally "verbal adverb" (even though these might more commonly be called "деепричастие").
# 
# Most verbal adverbs, along with most participles, are often referred to as "converbs" in the Turkology literature.
