# ==« Derivation » and friends==
# 
# The principle behind dealing with derivation is, as far as possible, that we don't want to deal with it. Derivation causes problems for translation because the translation of derivation is even more unpredictable than inflection. So, in general, just say no to derivation. However, if we want to get any kind of reasonable coverage, for each language, we're going to need to deal with about 5&mdash;10 suffixes which are very productive, and quite predictable in meaning.
# 
# ==="Abessive" case: -sIz ===
# The abessive or privative translates as "without" or "-less" in English.  It can be attributive, adverbial, or substantival.  The base reading is {{tag|advl}}, as with other postpositions. If we want {{tag|attr}} and {{tag|subst}} readings, then the word should be lexicalised as an adjective.
# 
# {|class=wikitable
# |-
# | Chuvash || -с{Ӑ}р 
# |-
# | Tatar, Kazakh, Kyrgyz  || -с{I}з
# |-
# | Turkish, Turkmen || -s{I}z
# |- 
# | Uzbek || -siz
# |}
# 
# ===The suffix -LI===
# 
# 
# {|class=wikitable
# |-
# | Tatar, Kazakh || -л{I}
# |-
# | Kyrgyz || -луу
# |-
# | Turkish, Turkmen || -l{I}
# |}
# 
# ===The suffix -LIK===
# 
# ===The suffix -KI===
# See [[Turkic languages/Ki]].
